Putting it together.

H-A, D-R, cost, and migration all share one discipline: measure first, design for the actual targets, and rehearse the recovery paths. Here's the consolidated playbook.

For high availability, span A-Zs by default for production tiers, use the native primitives, Multi-A-Z Auto Scaling Groups, R-D-S Multi-A-Z, and Aurora's six-copy storage layer, and trust S3, DynamoDB, and the managed services to do the A-Z work for you. For disaster recovery, quote R-T-O and R-P-O per workload, pick the matching shape, from Backup and Restore up through Pilot Light, Warm Standby, and Active-Active, and drill it quarterly; the building blocks are Aurora Global Database, DynamoDB Global Tables, S3 Cross-Region Replication, and Route 53 health-check failover. For cost, right-size weekly with Compute Optimizer, commit on the steady-state base with Savings Plans, burst on Spot, lifecycle your storage with Intelligent-Tiering, budget per team, and turn on Cost Anomaly Detection on day one. And for migration, pick the R per workload, lift-and-shift the bulk with M-G-N, move databases with D-M-S plus the S-C-T for heterogeneous ones, DataSync the file estates, and ship a Snowball for anything the network can't carry.

The cue map for the whole module: the two numbers that drive every resilience decision are R-T-O and R-P-O, per workload. The cheapest D-R and immutable backups across services is A-W-S Backup, with Vault Lock and cross-Region copy. Right-sizing recommendations come from Compute Optimizer. A discount on steady-state compute is Savings Plans, with Spot for burst. To alert before a budget overrun, A-W-S Budgets. To lift-and-shift servers and databases, M-G-N and D-M-S. And for petabytes the network can't carry, the Snow family. The through-line: resilience and cost are dials, not switches; set each one per workload to the target it actually needs.
